Southern Regional College holds the Erasmus+ VET Charter and the Erasmus HE Charter. 

Since 2007 the College has sent on average 120 VET students on mobility placement each year & in 2016 SRC sent 150 VET students.
 
SRC is committed to internationalisation and a new International Strategy was agreed in 2015 with KPIs.   Key objectives include:
> To widen the range of European exchange opportunities for staff and students by 20% each year to 2020 e.g. KA1;
>To increase the number of visits to European companies and host organisations by 10% each year to 2020;
>To facilitate the sharing of best practice with other regional colleges and international colleges and organisations e.g. KA2;
>To develop and implement a range of strategies supported through Information Systems and Technology that would further enhance European internationalisation; 
>To investigate and develop opportunities in ECVET;
>To increase European internships by 10% each year to 2020;
The Erasmus+ programme is viewed as being central to reaching these objectives.

The proposed MOVE IT project will send 170 VET learners  to undertake a two-week placement within various European situations.  This will enhance their knowledge, know-how, skills, competencies required in their particular occupations as well as build soft skills e.g. confidence, team-working, living and working in a global society.

The learners involved will be both initial VET (IVET) or continuous VET (CVET) undertaking work placements within a European setting tailored to meet their individual needs. Many of the learners live in areas of social deprivation and the majority will not have lived independently outside of Northern Ireland. The learners are from the following key curricula areas:

1.Construction
2. Health and Early Years
3  Applied Science 
4  Creative Design & Computing
5 Hospitality, Tourism Business & Management

Opportunities will be promoted to learners through senior and tutorial staff in each of the VET areas.  The students will complete application forms and selection will be made by a member of senior and tutorial staff.  Preparatory sessions will be held for both students and accompanying staff which will involve the logistical arrangements, geography and culture, language, food, transport, passport regulations, health, risk assessment (for staff), accommodation, pedagogical and learning agreements, use of reflective log as well as dissemination activities and their involvement.

Accompanying adults are vital in the planning, preparation, planning and engagement support. SRC have included accompanying adults as per our SRC EU policy, they will  be SRC tutors skilled in the vocational areas.  This endorses SRC's Internationalisation Strategy and Staff Development Policy ensuring staff are upskilled through networking with European partners, share pedagogical approaches and working practices, etc.

Each group of students will have an accompanying adult with them for the duration of their mobility placement to ensure the opportunities are maximised.  Their role will be to - 
- Provide ongoing support for participants whilst on placement;
- Monitor participants on placement and ensure the placements meets individual's needs and expectations;
- If applicable assess units /learning outcomes and validate participants' achievements;
- Attend any cultural/community activities with participants;
- Ensure they settle into their accommodation and participate in social/leisure activities, when appropriate;
- Participative actively in gaining feedback from students in relation to the placements;
- Ensure students complete their reflective learning log;
- Participate in the overall evaluation of the mobility project which will add to the planning of successive Erasmus+ projects.

SRC accompanying adults will have been briefed on their roles and responsibilities, the logistical arrangements, the key staff and contact arrangements, the students' learning agreements as well as their roles in complying with ECVET arrangements and subsequent assessment of learners, arrangements for mentoring as well as communications/key contacts for the duration of the mobility.  

On return all accompanying adults will complete formal feedback organised by SRC International team as well as 1:1 feedback.  Students will also complete evaluation forms on completion.  This is shared with curriculum managers for follow-up with students and staff.

All host partners will contribute to the evaluation of the project through formal feedback organised by SRC International team on completion, 1:1 conversations with accompanying adults on site as well as ongoing communications with Diana Farrelly, External Funding and Research Manager, SRC.   They will also be part of the dissemination plan for the project.  Activities include - articles and photos on their websites, appropriate local stakeholders' websites, SRC website, Colleges NI website, local press/media, social media and twitter accounts.

"It is widely recognised within education and mental health sectors that children and young peoples mental health and wellbeing has a huge impact on their ability to learn and achieve". (Worth-it- Wellbeing and resilience)

Prioritising wellbeing in schools has become vital. Our teachers and school staff have reported that they have insufficient knowledge about wellbeing or mental health to be able to confidently support their students. We feel we should care about our emotional health because of its effect on our students.  If we are to be healthy role models for our students and create happy, energetic, and safe learning environments, we must take good care of ourselves. The general aim of this training course is to foster excellence in education by empowering teachers, trainers, headmasters and other education staff to improve their stress management skills together with other teachers and education staff throughout all Europe gaining as well  a broader understanding of education in Europe and exchanging best practices and experiences. 

With such a huge amount of time spent in the classroom, schools provide an ideal environment for promoting good emotional wellbeing and identifying early behaviour changes and signs of mental distress. The social and emotional skills, knowledge and behaviours that young people learn in the classroom can help them to build resilience and set the pattern for how they will manage their mental health throughout their lives. Research has found that parents of children with mental health problems are most likely to seek advice or help from a teacher rather than any other professionals. So we need to be ready and equip with the essentials skills needed to support our staff, students and parents in their wellbeing. The schools approach should be supportive and therefore we consider this training course a great opportunity and foundation that will enable us to improve our stress management skills together with other teachers and education staff throughout all Europe gaining as well  a broader understanding of education in Europe and exchanging best practices and experiences.

Furthermore this course will offer us the opportunity to;
• Learn about the dynamics and characteristics of stress, its causes and its effects; 
• Get an insight into their individual patterns of stress response; 
• Practice and acquire concrete stress management techniques and tools; 
• Learn how to apply stress management tools to typical education situations (i.e. parent-teacher relationship, bullying, …); 
• Learn how to lead simple relaxation and visualization activities to ease students’ anxiety; 
• Exchange good practices and discuss challenges with fellow colleagues and the course trainers; 
• Make contacts with individuals and organizations working in the education field in Europe through everyday cooperation and networking activities; 
• Visit and network with Italian institutions. 

This course is extremely suitable to the needs of our organisation as it has been tailored to the working methods based upon participants’ needs, attitudes and professional profiles in order to ensure high productivity, effectiveness and transferability into practice. The methodology is highly practical and participative with hands-on approach that comprises real-job examples, case studies and simulations. Collaborative working methods are embraced that foster mutual learning and cooperation among participants.

